Disk Forensics > [T5]: Tracking NTFS File System Changes

(2) $UsnJrnl (Update Sequence Number Journal)

Another valuable artifact of the NTFS filesystem is $UsnJrnl, which provides high-level monitoring of file and folder changes, such as creation, deletion, and renaming. $USNJrnl file is located at "$Extend\$USNJrnl" under the drive root and stores data for days on a typical busy system.

$UsnJrnl itself does not hold data. It contains two other data streams; $J (where the most important data reside) and $Max.

 

$USNjrnl location - (zoom in)

  1. Drive root.
  2. $Extend folder.
  3. $UsnJrnl file.
  4. File size: As you may notice, the file size is 0 because, as we indicated earlier, $UsnJrnl itself does not hold data. It uses ADS to store data inside $J and $Max streams., To access $J content using FTKImager,  you just need to click on $USNJrnl in the Evidence tree window (left side).

 

$J location - (zoom in)

To analyze the $J, you can use KAPE to create a triage image, extract $UsnJrnl\$J and use "MFTEcmd" to parse it,  like what you did with $MFT. Then, you can load the produced CSV file in "Timeline Explorer".

 

$J content - (zoom in)

  1. File name
  2. File extension
  3. Entry Number
  4. Parent Entry number: If this record belongs to a file, this field will contain the parent folder entry number. This field will include the host file (that this stream is part of) entry number if it belongs to a data stream (ADS).
  5. Update reason contains changes that happened to the object, such as rename and deletion.
  6. The file attributes field contains attributes associated with the file (ex., hidden). Please check out this Microsoft resource for a detailed description of different attributes.
